On September 7, 2018, President Donald Trump issued a proclamation declaring September 7-9 as National Days of Prayer and Remembrance. The proclamation honors the memory of the nearly 3,000 innocent people who were killed in the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. It calls for prayer, contemplation, memorial services, visiting memorials, ringing bells, and candlelight remembrance vigils. The proclamation also emphasizes the resilience and unity of the nation in the face of the attacks and expresses gratitude for the first responders and other heroes who risked their lives to save others. It encourages future generations to understand the significance of this moment in American history and calls for guidance, wisdom, and protection for the men and women in uniform who fight against terrorism. The proclamation invites people around the world to join in the Days of Prayer and Remembrance.